{<b>Discarding a Loser</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> North opens 1\S. With 16 dummy points and support for all of the unbid
suits, East makes a takeout double.

Regardless of the takeout double, South holds nine points with spade support,
so raises to 2\S. South is too strong to recommend a weak 3\S response over the
takeout double.

North tries for game by rebidding 3\S, which South accepts holding a good hand
for her previous raise.

<b>Defense.</b> East leads the \CK, highest of touching honors. West discourages with
the \C3.

<b>Declarer play.</b> Declarer counts six sure winners and needs four more. Spades can
be promoted for four more winners.

Since this is a trump contract, declarer takes the additional step of checking
for fast losers. The lead will have to be surrendered twice to establish enough
winners, and the club lead has promoted two more fast losers in clubs. That's
too many losers.

Declarer looks for opportunities to discard a loser, and finds it in diamonds
where there is an extra winner in dummy. Declarer wins the \CA and immediately
plays \DQ-K-A, discarding a club loser. Now declarer can tackle spades. The
defense takes two spade tricks, but only one club trick.

<b>Key point.</b> Often when there is weakness in one suit, there is compensating
strength in another. In this deal, the extra strength in diamonds provided an
opportunity to eliminate a club loser. In putting it all together, declarer
couldn’t draw trumps first, since the opponents would get the lead and take
their club winners before declarer had discarded a loser.}
