{<b>Discarding a Loser</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> East passes and South opens 1\H. West holds 15 dummy points and
support for all of the unbid suits, so doubles for takeout.

North holds four-card support for hearts, but with such a weak hand otherwise,
not to mention the vulnerability, declines to raise to 3\H, which would be weak
over the takeout double.

East holds 11 points, so advances by jumping to 2\S. West judges that game is
possible, so raises to 3\S. East holds a maximum for her previous bidding, so
bids game.

<b>Defense.</b> South has three defensive tricks, and leads the fourth-best \H5 trying
to develop a fourth trick in hearts. North plays \HQ, third hand high, so that
declarer doesn't win an undeserved trick with the \HJ.

<b>Declarer play.</b> Four sure tricks, needing six more. Three more tricks can be
promoted in spades, and three more in diamonds. That's 10 tricks, but check the
loser situation.

Declarer has three sure losers, and the heart lead has established another.
That's too many. Declarer has an extra winner in clubs, so before playing
spades (or diamonds), declarer plays \n
\CK-Q-A, discarding the heart loser.

Now declarer tackles trumps. After trumps are drawn in two rounds, declarer
tackles diamonds. The defense takes only two spades and a diamond trick.

<b>Key point.</b> Declarer has to eliminate the heart loser before letting the
opponents have the lead. On this deal, that means trumps can’t be played
(because the opponents would get the lead) until declarer gets rid of the \HJ
on the extra club winner.}
