{<b>Ruffing a Loser</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> If West adds a point for her five-card diamond suit and opens 1NT, the
auction might get very interesting. North holds enough to make a standard
penalty double, which South will pass, hoping to defeat 1NT. If West stays the
course and also passes, she will find that 1NT is unbeatable, despite
North-South holding the balance of strength.

If West opens 1\D, North-South should get to hearts. North holds 18 dummy
points and support for all of the unbid suits, so doubles for takeout. East
passes, and South advances with 1\H.

North holds 19 dummy points and knows that game is still possible, even though
South holds less than eight points. North raises to 2\H, but South holds a
minimum and passes.

<b>Defense.</b> West leads the \DA, highest of touching honors. East encourages with
the \D9, which might be a doubleton. West continues with the \DK and a low
diamond.

<b>Declarer play.</b> Glad to be no higher than 2\H, declarer counts six sure winners
and needs two more. A diamond ruff in dummy will provide another, as will heart
length. Another trick might come from spade length.

A count of losers reveals two in hearts and two in diamonds, so no worries
about fast losers.

After ruffing a diamond, declarer should pull trumps. It is good technique to
duck a round of hearts, but playing the \HA does no harm on this deal.

<b>Key point.</b> Declarer can gain winners by ruffing losers in the dummy. Declarer
often has to manage the trump suit carefully in order to both ruff losers and
draw the missing trumps.}
