{<b>Ruffing a Loser</b>

<b>Bidding.</b> West passes and North opens 1\C, preferring to open 1\C when 3–3 in
the minors.

Holding 14 dummy points and support for all of the unbid suits, East doubles
for takeout.

South holds enough to compete to 2\C. Over 2\C, West need not bid. But, with
eight points, West judges that 2\H will have a chance.

<b>Defense.</b> Considering South's raise, North leads the \C3, low from an honor.
South plays the \CJ, third hand only just as high as necessary.

<b>Declarer play.</b> Declarer counts four sure winners and needs four more. Two can
be promoted in diamonds, and another will come from heart length if the
defender's hearts divide 3-2, as is likely. A club ruff will suffice for an
eighth trick.

To conserve entries, declarer ducks the opening club lead. Then declarer can
win the club continuation in hand to ruff a club in dummy.

Ducking a heart might expose declarer to a ruff, so declarer next cashes the
\HA-K. Leaving a high trump outstanding, declarer now tackles diamonds.
Declarer scores one spade, two high hearts and a heart trick by length in hand,
two diamonds, one club, and a club ruff. The defense is held to two spades, one
heart, one diamond, and one club.

<b>Key point.</b> Declarer can eliminate a loser in hand by ruffing it in the dummy.}
